Code Review


What it is
A terminal-based AI assistant/companion project — combining conversational memory (via Gemini's google.genai types), text-to-speech (SAPI), an animated ASCII "robot face" CLI interface (via rich), and a weather utility. Reads like an in-progress passion project, which lines up with your own comment about the robot faces still being under development.
Strengths


Reasonable separation of concerns — memory handling, speech, UI, and utilities each live in their own file/module.
Nice UX touch: the slow_print typing effect with punctuation-based pacing (longer pauses on ./!/?, shorter on ,/:/;) makes the CLI feel more alive than a flat print statement.
Graceful degradation: init_speaker() returns None on failure instead of crashing, and speak_text checks for that before calling .Speak().
Clear intent behind the ASCII banner and mood-based robot face — a fun, distinctive interface choice rather than a generic CLI.


Things to tighten up
Bare except: clauses (init_speaker, save_history) catch everything, including things you don't want silently swallowed (like KeyboardInterrupt). Use except Exception: at minimum, or be specific (except (AttributeError, KeyError):).
Manual file handling instead of context managers — f = open(...); ...; f.close() will leak the file handle if an exception occurs in between. Use with open(memory_file, 'r') as f:.
No error handling in get_weather — a network timeout or connection error will raise an uncaught exception instead of falling through to your friendly error message. Wrap the request in try/except requests.RequestException.
faces dict rebuilt on every call to get_robot_face() — move it to a module-level constant since it never changes.




On the use of AI in this project
This reads as human-written with AI likely used as a helper along the way — a pretty normal workflow.
My reasoning:
The stylistic inconsistencies (bare excepts, manual open/close, informal error strings like "Weather API is acting up again.") are things a human writes that an AI assistant, left alone, tends to clean up. A one-shot AI generation would more likely show uniform patterns — context managers, docstrings, type hints throughout.
The unpolished in-progress comment about robot faces still being under development is a strong signal of a real person tracking their own project status, not something typically found in AI-authored code.
Some individual functions (slow_print, get_robot_face) do have a clean, self-contained "textbook example" quality — but that's just as consistent with a human following a tutorial pattern as with AI-assisted snippets, so it's not a reliable signal either way.


Bottom line: this looks like an incrementally built personal project, possibly with some AI-assisted pieces, but not a wholesale AI-generated codebase. I can't verify authorship from code alone — and neither can AI detectors, reliably. If you ever need to demonstrate this, version control history (commit timestamps, messy WIP diffs) is much stronger evidence than code style.
